Who is Jaribha? Not who, but what - Jaribha is an online platform that facilitates and manages contributions, allowing project owners also known as Creators to share their projects to get Supporters to contribute and make their projects come to life. The website allows Creators to develop and detail their projects on their own individual pages and gain support through Supporters that want to support projects based on their own personal interests and reaping token and modest rewards. Who is the Creator? The Creator is any project owner on Jaribha, or any person submitting an idea on Jaribha that desires exposure, feedback and community support to reach the Project Goal following the all-or-nothing method. Who is the Supporter? The person contributing to a project. They can be friends, family or simply any member of the community who has supported a project. What is a Community? A community is a social unit of any size that shares common values. An individual can create a project and choose the community they belong to, thus giving Creators a sense of credibility, and the community good exposure. How can I connect to Jaribha on social media? Creating a project How do I create a project? If you have a project or an idea that you want to see come to life, you can submit it here Start a Project . You must ensure your project follows all Jaribha guidelines and requirements. As a Creator on Jaribha, you are responsible in creating videos, content, images and plans of your idea or project, as well as list the total amount of support you will need to raise in order to execute it. You must also create different support categories and amounts, which also include rewards for each support category. The number of support categories is up to you the Creator. Does Jaribha process and review all projects before they launch? Do all submitted projects get approved? Community Steps A community is a social unit of any size that shares common values. An individual can create a project and choose the community they belong to, thus giving Creators a sense of credibility, and the community good exposure. Click on Add new Community on the communities page. Fill out the form. Jaribha will review the information and email the Community with a response. If approved, the Community will go live. Creators Steps To become a Creator, an individual must choose to create a project. Create an account and sign in Click\nStart your Project Fill out the application Wait for Approval If approved, the project will go online for the alloted time period. If project is not approved, the Creator may be asked to sort out some issues within the project. After the allotted period ends\nthe creator would have Not reached their Project Goal. An unsuccessfully supported project Reached their Project Goal or surpassed it. A successfully supported project Learn more at Help Center Sponsors Steps A Sponsor has to pay a fee to be seen on the project page.1 Click on \'Become a Sponsor\' button. Fill out the form, send it and wait to be contacted by us. After the payment is made it is will appear on the project page. Awaits to see if the project is successful\nor unsuccessful in reaching the Goal\nAmount. If the project is unsuccessful, the creator\'s Sponsor fee will be refunded minus the processing fee(3%). If project successfully reaches its goal amountn the sponsor will not receive a reward, unless otherwise. Supporters Steps We call this person the \'Supporter\' because he/she is supporting the Creator to reach the Project Goal for a reward in return. Browse to look for a project to support. Find a project. When a decision is made to support a project the Supporter will be directed to a payment portal. If the project is unsuccessful, the Supporter will receive the amount supported back minus the processing fee (3%) If the project is successful, the Creator will contact the Supporter in regards to the reward promised, if any. How will Infusion KW use the $500 if raised? Making a dream, a reality… I wouldn\'t call it a hobby but a lifestyle. The Beginning The kitchen remained largely unaffected by architectural advances throughout the Middle Ages; open fire remained the only method of heating food. European medieval kitchens were dark, smoky, and sooty places, whence their name. In European medieval cities around the 10th to 12th centuries, the kitchen still used an open fire hearth in the middle of the room. In wealthy homes, the ground floor was often used as a stable while the kitchen was located on the floor above, like the bedroom and the hall. In castles and monasteries, the living and working areas were separated; the kitchen was sometimes moved to a separate building, and thus could not serve anymore to heat the living rooms. In some castles the kitchen was retained in the same structure, but servants were strictly separated from nobles, by constructing separate spiral stone staircases for use of servants to bring food to upper levels. An extant example of such a medieval kitchen with servants\' staircase is at Muchalls Castle in Scotland. In Japanese homes, the kitchen started to become a separate room within the main building at that time. When i get a new Supporter every time When i get a new Sponsor every time When my Project receives a comment When one of the Projects I supported reaches its deadline When one of the Projects I supported has been updated Projects with open Platinum Sponsor spaces General Newletter (When i received a private message Update on new projects and successful projects Successfully Supported! Supported Amount Please choose one of the following and add a comment if you choose: Update 1 Add Update If you want to access all features go on the website. (Only cteator does this) Rewards are a token of appreciation provided by the Creators to thank all those who have contributed to the project. Rewards should be creative, tangible and not overpriced. Rewards should relate back to the project. For example, if th